<HEADLINE> Philippine President Orders Austerity Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos on Saturday ordered the launch of an austerity program for
the government for fiscal year 1998 in the wake of the financial
turmoil sweeping much of Asia.
</P>
<P>
Ramos directed all government departments and agencies,
including state universities, government-owned and controlled
corporations and local government units, to reduce expenditures by
at least 25 percent of authorized regular appropriations.
</P>
<P>
"The current economic difficulties brought about by the peso
depreciation requires continued prudence in government fiscal
management to maintain economic stability and sustain the
country's growth momentum," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ramos stressed the need for all government units "to adopt cash
management measures to match expenditures with available
resources."
</P>
<P>
He ordered the suspension of a series of activities for
government units, including establishment of new agencies, most
capital or infrastructure projects and foreign trips by government
personnel.
</P>
<P>
Ramos asked government agencies to report on the estimated
savings generated from the austerity measures.
</P>
<P>
The peso has fallen by 52 percent from 26.2 pesos to 40 pesos
to the dollar. Analysts and international organizations expect the
Philippine economy to further slow down in 1998 as a result of the
financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
