<HEADLINE> Iran: Ready for Dialog With Neighbors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian Foreign Ministry
spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi said here today that Iran welcomes
dialog with its neighboring states to foster regional cooperation
and friendship.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Iran's official news agency IRNA,
Mohammadi said that reinforcement of relations with the
neighboring states, including the members of the Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC), tops the agenda of Iran's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the timetable for the reported visit to
the United Arab Emirates of Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi has not been finalized so far.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that Kharrazi would started his tour to
Abu Dhabi soon after the end of the GCC summit held in Kuwait a
week ago. At the summit, the GCC leaders announced their support
for talks between Iran and the UAE to solve their territorial
disputes over three islands in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Both Iran and the UAE announced to have full sovereignty over
the islands of Abu Musa, the Greater and the Lesser Tunbs at the
mouth of the strategic Hormoz Strait. Tehran took over the islands
after the British forces withdrew from the region in 1971.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the UAE President Zayed Bin Sultan
Al-Nahyan has agreed with the proposal of his Iranian
counterpart Mohammad Khatami to hold bilateral talks to solve
the dispute.
</P>
<P>
"We have attached special importance to our relations with the
Islamic states and are willing to settle mutual issues in parallel
with developing bilateral or multi-lateral cooperation with them,"
Mohammadi said.
</P>
<P>
He said the summit of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference (OIC) held here on December 9-11 has led to a
common sense of cooperation in the region, serving the
security and the interests of the regional nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
