<HEADLINE> Russia to Increase Import Duties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The Russian government has
decided to impose import quotas and increase import duties
in a bid to protect its domestic market.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics from the Russian Ministry of Economic
Relations and Trade, starting from January 1, 1998, Russia will
limit carpets imports from the European Union (EU) countries to 16
million square meters worth 100-110 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In addition, higher duties will be levied on the imports of
baby food, dairy products, poultry meat, alcoholic drinks, and
second-hand and new automobiles, which have flooded the Russian
market in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Tariff on eggs imported from outside the Commonwealth of
Independent States will rise from 10 percent to 22 percent and
those on alcoholic drinks from 15-26 percent to 180-185 percent,
duties on imported second-hand automobiles will double.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the Russian customs authorities said that Russia
lost 700 million U.S. dollars in the past year as EU levied
anti-dumping taxes and high customs duties on some of Russian
products.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, with large amount of commodities flooding in from EU
countries, two thirds of the food markets in big Russian cities
have been dominated by foreign products and over 90 percent of
color TV sets sold in Russia are imported ones.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Russia will lower about one third of import
duties on new automobiles and stop taxation on imported
unprocessed diamonds in an effort to gain an early entry into the
World Trade Organization and an integration into the international
economic system and to enhance the quality of the products of the
domestic industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
