<HEADLINE> Some 100,000 Bosnian Refugees Repatriated From Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 27 (Xinhua) -- About 100,000 among a total of
350,000 Bosnian war refugees living in Germany have returned home
in 1997, a German press report said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Dietmar Schlee, the German government's envoy
for refugee affairs, as saying that about 170,000 to 180,000 of
the 250,000 Bosnian refugees remaining in Germany are from the
Serb Republic of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The situation in the republic was so "miserable" that
repatriation operations must be combined with reconstruction
programs, said Schlee in an interview with the German Frankfurter
Rundschau newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The number of Bosnian refugees absorbed by Germany since 1992
are far more than that accepted by any other European countries.
</P>
<P>
However, uneasy with the heavy financial burden of hosting the
refugees, which was estimated at 3 billion U.S. dollars a year,
local German authorities have mounted increasing pressure this
year on the refugees to return home voluntarily. Otherwise, they
could face deportations.
</P>
<P>
But Germany's hard-line repatriation plans have met with strong
criticism, not only from the refugees, but also from the United
States. The latter called on Germany early this year not to
repatriate those refugees for fear of possible ethnic violence in
the republic.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, German officials insisted that since the fighting
had stopped, Bosnian refugees should return home to participate in
the rebuilding of their country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
