<DOCNO> XIE19971228.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-27 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Raises Commercial Duties on Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Iran has raised commercial
imports duties from 4.2 percent to 10 percent, Commerce Minister
Mohammad Shariatmadar announced today.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA quoted Shariatmadar as saying
the Iranian cabinet's decision became effective on December 22.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that the rate increase would not affect the
import of basic commodities and the raw material for
pharmaceutical as well as industrial products. Presently, 70
percent of the imports are not subject to new commercial duties,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Changing commercial duties are within the jurisdiction of the
cabinet while any adjustments in customs tariffs have to be
approved by Majlis (parliament), Shariatmadar explained.
</P>
<P>
He stated that the rate change would have a positive impact on
domestic industries, adding that the government expects a revenue
of 2,500 billion rials (833 million U.S. dollars) from commercial
duties in the budget of the new Iranian fiscal year (starts on
March 21). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
