<HEADLINE> PNA Urges Israel to Implement Security Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) has urged the Israeli government to implement the
joint security agreement and confiscate weapons from Jewish
settlers, Jerusalem Media and Communication Center (JMCC) reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The PNA considered as a serious provocative act the planned
attempt by two radical Jewish settlers to throw a pig's head
wrapped in pages of the Koran into the Al-Aqsa Mosque in East
Jerusalem during the upcoming Muslim's holy month of Ramadan
starting next week.
</P>
<P>
This is one reason why the PNA asking for the implementation of
the joint security agreement reached between the Israel and the
PNA, JMCC said.
</P>
<P>
The joint security agreement, also called the memorandum of
understanding, was reached by the security chiefs of the PNA and
Israel in association with the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency
representatives on December 17.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Arafat has already approved this
document, but Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said on
Wednesday that it is unacceptable and he will not sign it.
</P>
<P>
The two radical Jewish settlers have already been arrested by
the Israeli police for their controversial plan of action.
</P>
<P>
The plan has caused furious reaction from the PNA side. PNA
Minister of Islamic Waqf Sheikh Hassan Tahboub today warned of the
dangers of this plan and held the Israeli government completely
responsible for any future acts.
</P>
<P>
PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat said in Gaza today that this plan,
if being carried out, would totally destroy the Middle East peace
process. He urged the Israeli government to consider seriously the
consequences of such acts if they occur.
</P>
<P>
Arafat also urged the Israeli government to confiscate weapons
from Jewish settlers, because there were reports of more
conflicts between settlers and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He urged Netanyahu to implement the joint security agreement,
which has laid down foundations of mutual security cooperations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
