<DOCNO> XIE19971228.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Telephone Industry Growing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Strong economy and new
technology have stimulated the development of the telephone
industry in the United States with household cellular phone
penetration expected to grow to 53.2 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
The penetration rate at 1997 is 25.8 percent, reported local
newspaper Investor's Business Daily today, citing private
statistics and figures of the Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
Telephone is forecast to reach 105.5 million homes in 2000 from
102.1 million in 1997. The latest edition of World Almanac put
total U.S. households at 91,947,410 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the number of local telephone lines grew 4 percent to
172 million, while phone use soared by 5 percent to chalk a
revenue of 108 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
About 20 percent of homes now have a second telephone line, up
from 3 percent in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Cellular phone customers numbered 40 million in 1996 and the
market is growing much faster than expected.
</P>
<P>
Since the U.S. Congress passed telecommunications reform two
years ago, the 262-billion-dollar-plus phone and cable TV market
has been opened to competition.
</P>
<P>
To cope with the situation, the local phone industry has
invested 20 billion dollars a year in basic network systems.
</P>
<P>
Three of the largest mergers in U.S. corporate history have
taken place in the wake of the reform, with U.S. second largest
telephone company MCI agreeing in November to be acquired by U.S.
fourth largest long-distance telephone firm WorldCom in a 37
billion dollar deal.
</P>
<P>
Expected to cover 2 million customers, the unprecedented merger
in U.S. history may pose challenges to other telecommunications
companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
