<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Ready to Export Oil Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Oil Minister Amir
Mohammed Rashid today asserted his country's readiness to export
crude oil to world markets soon after the ratification of the new
food distribution plan from the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The oil reservoirs in the seaports of Iraq's Bakr and Turkey's
Ceyhan are ready for the export and contain large quantities of
oil, Rashid told reporters after talks with Jordanian Minister of
Energy and Mineral Resources Mohamed Saleh Hourani here.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq will give priority to the oil firms of friendly
countries in signing deals under the third stage of the
oil-for-food deal with the U.N..
</P>
<P>
The oil purchase contracts will be similar to those signed
between Iraq and world oil firms in the first and second stages of
the deal, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, which came into force a year ago, Iraq is
allowed to pump 1 million barrels of oil per day to get 2 billion
U.S. dollars every six months to buy medicines and other
humanitarian goods.
</P>
<P>
Iraq earlier announced that it will not export oil until it
receives ratification from the U.N. for the new food distribution
plan for the third phase of the deal.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi oil minister held the U.S. administration responsible
for obstructing the implementation of the oil-for-food deal and
the delay in the arrival of foodstuffs and medicines to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Jordanian minister said that Jordan this year
received 4.2 million tonnes of Iraqi crude oil and by-products,
which represents 7 percent growth over the quota of last year.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have agreed on several oil projects under the
protocol on cooperation of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi experts also took part in the updating of a Jordanian
oil field and the building of a pipeline for carrying Iraqi oil
to Jordan and a refining plant in Al-Aqaba, Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Hourani added that Jordan hopes to increase its imports of
Iraqi crude oil and by-products by 7 per cent next year to meet
its domestic needs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
