<HEADLINE> Egyptians Barred From Key Posts in Qatar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Qatar has stopped renewing
work contracts for Egyptians occupying sensitive posts in Qatar
since ties between the two countries began fraying in November,
the Qatari News Agency (QNA) said today.
</P>
<P>
"Contracts for about 500 Egyptians working for the armed
forces, the Emir's palace, the intelligence services and in some
cases, Qatar University, were not renewed when they expired," the
QNA said.
</P>
<P>
Qatar relies on skillful and experienced foreign manpower in
many sectors and two-thirds of its 600,000 population are
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Egyptians began losing their jobs after the beginning of the
crisis between the two countries, triggered by a war of words on
November's Middle East and North Africa economic conference which
was hosted by Doha but boycotted by Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The two countries appeared to have reconciled their
differences at a December 3 summit in Riyadh sponsored by Saudi
Arabia. But the bilateral relations still remain cool. 
</P>
