<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971228.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Kenya's Major Opposition Candidates for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Michael Kijana Wamalwa and
Raila Odinga, leaders of Kenya's two major opposition parties --
FORD-Kenya and National Development Party (NDP), are seen as two
of the "Big Five" in Kenya's 1997 15-member presidential race.
</P>
<P>
Their chances of winning the presidency in Monday's poll are
slim in contrast with those of incumbent President Daniel arap
Moi, Democratic Party chief Mwai Kibaki and Social Democratic
Party's female hopeful Charity Ngilu but much more brilliant than
the rest 10.
</P>
<P>
Official leader of the opposition and a lawmaker, Wamalwa is
regarded as one of the finest orators in the parliament in the
eastern African country. His FORD-Kenya is the only party in the
country with a parliamentary representative in each province.
</P>
<P>
He once was said the darling of Kenyan youth and intellectuals
but lost many of his own supporters in the past two years due to
his pro-government stance in a number of high profile political
scandals.
</P>
<P>
When he was the Chairman of the Public Accounts Committee, he
absolved Kamlesh Pattni of involvement in the export compensation
scandal in which about 330 million U.S. Dollars went missing.
</P>
<P>
Later he said Ketan Somaia, another Kenyan businessman of
Asian descent, need not appear before the committee to account
for alleged failure to carry out a seven-million-Dollar contract.
</P>
<P>
He thereafter was thought by many people to have been in
secret deals with the government over these and other matters.
</P>
<P>
His party is seen to be dominated mainly by his fellow
tribesmen, the Baluhyas. As a result, he has got much of Luhya
support in Western Province, part of the Rift Valley, Nyanza,
Nairobi and the Coast. Luhya is the third largest tribe in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Born to a wealthy family in Kitale, western Kenya, in
November, 1944, he gained a degree in law from King's College,
Cambridge in 1968 and a Master degree in international law from
the London School of Economics and then lectured in law at
Nairobi University from 1970 to 1976.
</P>
<P>
In 1974, a 30-year-old Wamalwa contested the Kitale West
parliamentary seat in Rift Valley Province but failed. It was at
that time he was nicknamed "Kijana" ("youth" in Kiswahili),
implying that he was still too young to make it in politics.
</P>
<P>
He won the seat in 1979. In 1988, he became a parliamentary
member for Saboti and was appointed as the Parliamentary
Secretary of the ruling Kenya African National Union (KANU), then
the sole legal political party in the country.
</P>
<P>
After the introduction of pluralism in 1991, Wamalwa became
the second vice-chairman of the original FORD (Forum for the
Restoration of Democracy) in September 1992. When the party split
afterwards, he joined Raila Odinga's faction FORD-Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Wamalwa was confirmed as the chairman of FORD-Kenya in January
1997 when finally he defeated Odinga in the inner-party power
struggle. Odinga then quit FORD-Kenya and joined the SDP.
</P>
<P>
Like Wamalwa, Odinga's support is also mainly from his own
tribesmen -- he commands broad support in western Kenya,
especially among young people from his Luo tribe, the second
largest in the country.
</P>
<P>
Second son of Kenya's first Vice President and "Father of the
Kenyan Opposition" Jaramogi Oginga Odinga, Raila was born in
Maseno, Kisumu, Nyanza Province in January, 1945.
</P>
<P>
Winning a high school scholarship in 1961 to study in the then
East Germany, he attended the Herder Institute and thereafter the
Magdeburg College of Advanced Technology, graduating in 1970 with
a Master degree in mechanical engineering.
</P>
<P>
On return to Kenya, he became an assistant lecturer in
mechanical engineering at Nairobi University and later got
involved in his father's business as the managing director of a
factory making gas cylinders.
</P>
<P>
In 1978, he founded Applied Engineering Services, a consulting
firm specializing in industrial projects consultancy and
municipal engineering.
</P>
<P>
He has been detained three times by the Moi government. The
first was in 1982 with charges of planning the failed Air Force
coup to topple Moi's rule.
</P>
<P>
In September 1988, seven months after his release, he was
again picked up without charge. He was set free in June 1989,
only to be re-arrested in July 1990 and held for 11 months for
alleged involvement with the Kenya Revolutionary Movement.
</P>
<P>
After the third detention which occurred during the height of
the agitation for multi-partyism, he fled to Norway in October,
1991 following a wave of attacks and harassment by state security
personnel.
</P>
<P>
He returned in February 1992 and was elected the vice chairman
of FORD. When FORD was soon afterwards split into FORD-Kenya and
FORD-Asili, he was elected deputy director of elections in the
former before he quit in January.
</P>
<P>
He was a prominent member of the National Convention Executive
Council (NCEC), the umbrella body of the opposition set up in
April which successfully organized nationwide strikes and rallies
to press the government for minimum constitutional reforms before
the elections.
</P>
<P>
"Having been born in a political family, politics to me is a
way of life," Odinga said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
