<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Digs Geothermal Wells </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Two deep geothermal wells
with a capacity of three mega watt of geothermal energy were
commissioned today in afar region of Ethiopia with 7.6 million
birr (about 1.1 million U.S. Dollars) allocated by the
government.
</P>
<P>
The two deep geothermal wells, which would be completed in
three months, are the second phase deep well sinking of the
Tendaho geothermal survey project in the north-eastern afar
region.
</P>
<P>
Negassie Mekuria, general manager of the project, was quoted
by a local report as saying that a total of five mega watt of
energy are expected to be generated with the completion of the
second phase of the project.
</P>
<P>
Four deep wells were sunk with the 32 million dollars obtained
from the Italian government during the first phase three years
ago. Two of the wells generate two mega watts of geothermal
energy. 
</P>
