<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 27 (Xinhua) -- French Minister in Charge of
Relations with Parliament, Daniel Vaillant, said today that there
is no "sword of Damocles" of a dissolution of government by
President Jacques Chirac, who is cohabiting with the Socialists.
</P>
<P>
Vaillant was responding to a statement made last week by former
transport minister Bernard Pons, who is a close friend of
Chirac's, that "the power to dissolve (government by Chirac) is a
sword of Damocles on the government and the National Assembly."
</P>
<P>
Both Vaillant and Pons made their declarations in the Sunday
newspaper "Le Journal du Dimanche".
</P>
<P>
Vaillant said that the legitimacy of the government and its
parliamentary majority are not jeopardized, and he did not see any
condition suitable for a dissolution.
</P>
<P>
"One governs on the basis of a popular will and a confidence in
the action of the prime minister and government," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Chirac has given his confidence to Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin, who he said "makes the French people feel safe"
through his policy, method and will to hold dialogue. 
