<HEADLINE> New Ore Port to Be Built in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Tangshan, a major
industrial city in north China, has recently signed an agreement
with the Capital Iron and Steel Corp., one of the country's most
powerful state-owned enterprises, to jointly build a new ore port
at Caofeidian, Tangshan City.
</P>
<P>
The large-scale ore port, another such project to be built
along Bohai Bay after Tianjin Port in north China, will be put
into operation by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Caofeidian, 38 nautical miles from north China's Tianjin port,
is the only site appropriate for building berths with a handling
capacity exceeding 200,000 tons in the middle coast along Bohai
Bay, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the new port is expected to greatly improve
the transportation of mineral resources, which is especially
important for the development of the iron and steel industry in
north China.  
