<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Launch One Satellite Every Year Till 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 28 (Xinhua) -- The Indian Space Research
Organization (ISRO) plans to launch one remote sensing satellite
every year till 2002, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The remote sensing satellite will be launched by using
indigenously developed payloads from India's own launch pads, PTI
said, quoting the project director of ISRO's Indian remote sensing
program, Dr. S. Kalayanaraman.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of launching one such satellite every year is to
maintain continuity in service since the life period of a
satellite is approximately three years. The satellite will be
useful for various fields of study and research with remote
sensing methods.
</P>
<P>
The next remote sensing satellite in the Indian remote
satellite (IRS) series, IRS-p4, to be launched next year, will be
an operational satellite taking care of oceanographic studies. It
will scan ocean, study water heights and wave movements, gather
data on coastlines and have limited land applications.
</P>
<P>
IRS-p5, to be launched in 1999, will concentrate on
cartographic studies. It will also be useful in urban planning,
Kalayanaraman said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971228.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exchange Rates of Renminbi Yuan To Remain Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 26 (Xinhua) --The exchange rates of Renminbi
yuan will remain stable and will not be forced to change due to
negative effects of the recent financial turmoil in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
According to an article published last week by Economic Daily,
one of the major Chinese official papers, the recent financial
crisis in Southeast and East Asia has seriously devalued many
major currencies.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Baht was depreciated by nearly 50 percent, with both
the Indonesian Rupiah and the Republic of Korea's Won devaluated
by more than 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
The currency of China's Taiwan island was also devalued by 20
percent, even though it has a large foreign exchange reserve.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that exchange rate changes will not only affect
China's exports to Southeast and East Asia, but also comparatively
increase their cost of importing China-made products.
</P>
<P>
Some have concluded that it is unfavorable for China to export
its labor-intensive products if the yuan is not devalued and its
exchange rates remain unchanged. Southeast Asian states could be
more competitive after devaluation of their currencies.
</P>
<P>
However, exchange rates for the yuan have not fallen since the
beginning of the Southeast Asia financial turmoil. The Chinese
Renminbi has maintained a stable exchange rate against major
overseas currencies.
</P>
<P>
From July to October, when Southeast Asia was badly hit by
speculation in financial markets, China's foreign exchange reserve
increased by 17 billion U.S. dollars, which drove the country's
total up to 137.9 billion U.S. dollars at the end of October.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of Renminbi with the U.S. dollar in
mid-August was 8.29-to-1. However, it remained at 8.2796-to-1 at
the end of November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971228.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exchange Rates of Yuan To Remain Stable (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Few believe that the Renminbi will be devalued, according to
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
First, unlike most Southeast Asian states, China does not have
an imbalance in current accounts, which would directly lead to
devaluation of the Chinese yuan.
</P>
<P>
China's exchange rates are mainly influenced by macro-economic
control measures at home, and not necessarily by the adjustment of
exchange rates by Southeast Asian states.
</P>
<P>
If China continues its moderately tight financial policy and
avoids risks of an overheated domestic demand, the paper said, the
country should maintain a balanced account of foreign trade next
year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, China has lowered bank interest rates three times
since early 1996, and the inflation rate has remained at a low
level because of China's successful economic soft-landing.
</P>
<P>
All these factors will help improve the competitiveness of
Chinese export enterprises, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Also, China's foreign trade surplus will exceed 40 billion
U.S. dollars by the end of this year, which will protect China's
foreign trade industry from being seriously hurt by market
changes, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Southeast Asian states need time to rein in their
fluctuating exchange rates, and the rising interest rates and
inflation rate, which will undermine their efforts to increase
exports.
</P>
<P>
Even if China's foreign trade was affected, the country would
have no deficit in current accounts next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971228.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exchange Rates of Yuan To Remain Stable (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Second, it is impossible that the escape of overseas investment
from China would cause devaluation of the Renminbi yuan, the paper
said. Overseas investors still favor the business opportunities in
the China market, and are confident in China's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
China has maintained a steady economic growth during recent
years, and the improved investment environment will help the
country pool funds for construction of infrastructure projects and
attract overseas investments.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, direct overseas cash flow to
China has been increasing in recent years although the country's
contractual overseas investment is declining.
</P>
<P>
From January to October the total overseas investment in China
reached 41.9 billion U.S. dollars, up 26.9 percent from the same
period last year. Direct overseas investment accounted for nearly
80 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Most of the overseas direct investments have long-term targets,
which lowers the risks of a sudden flight of overseas investment
from China.
</P>
<P>
Third, rumors about possible devaluation of Renminbi at home
will not influence market supply and demand much, the paper said,
because the Chinese yuan can only be freely converted under
current accounts and the country tightly controls capital inflow
and outflow.
</P>
<P>
The limited convertibility prevents China from being hurt by
speculators in the international financial market. That is also
why China has survived the financial turmoils in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rates of the yuan were decided by the market after
China reformed its system in 1994. The central bank, the People's
Bank of China, can only prevent sharp changes in the exchange
rates.
</P>
<P>
It is impossible for the central bank to take the full risk of
devaluing the yuan while ignoring market trends, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
It is reasonable to believe that the exchange rates of Chinese
yuan will remain stable, but the paper warned that market dealers
must make rational judgements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
