<HEADLINE> Jordan's FM Ends Visit to Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's Minister of
State for Foreign Affairs Fayez Tarawneh left Riyadh today
after his two-day visit to Saudi Arabia aimed at breaking the
deadlocked Middle East peace process and boosting bilateral
relations.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Saudi Arabia, Tarawneh met with King Fahd
Bin Abdula Aziz and Crown Prince Abdallah and delivered a message
from King Hussein to Fahd on the stagnant Middle East Peace
process and its negative implications on peace and stability in
the region.
</P>
<P>
He also held talks with his Saudi counterpart Prince Saud
Al-Faisal on issues related to the staled Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers conducted a full evaluation of the
dangers facing the Middle East peace march in light of Israel's
ignorance of international efforts to compel it to return to the
peace track, according to Kuwait News Agency (KUNA).
</P>
<P>
They expressed their countries' increasing concern over the
continuing Israeli hard-line policy against the Arabs and its
refusal to implement the peace agreements with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
They expressed hope that the Israeli government would be aware
of its policy's repercussions and its unilateral vision of
security, the KUNA quoted diplomatic sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
They called on the international community, especially the
United States and Russia, to exert pressure against Israel. The
two countries share the same view regarding the Middle East peace
process which is based on the principle of land-for-peace and
U.N. resolutions on the Arab-Israeli conflict.
</P>
<P>
Their talks also dealt with means of boosting bilateral ties,
especially in the economic, commercial and investments fields.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh's visit follows the official visit to Saudi Arabia by
Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan in September.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Saudi Arabia and Jordan have been improving
in recent years after several years' strain following the Gulf
War in 1991 when Amman stood on the side of Iraq while Saudi
Arabia was one of the allies led by the U.S. to liberate Kuwait
from Iraqi seven-month occupation.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is Jordan's second largest trading partner after
Iraq. In 1996, Jordan exported about 184 million U.S. dollars
worth of goods to Saudi Arabia compared to 99 million U.S.
dollars in 1995, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Under a trade protocol, the two countries are expected to
set up a free trade zone by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
