<HEADLINE> 9 Million Kenyans Set to Vote in Monday's General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 28 (Xinhua) -- A total of 9,030,141
registered Kenyan voters are expected to cast their ballots
across the country on Monday to decide who will be the fittest
person to lead the eastern African country into next millennium.
</P>
<P>
One president, 210 parliamentary members and 2,955 local
councillors will be elected on Monday's second democratic
multi-party general elections in Kenya with a population of
around 28 million.
</P>
<P>
In the most crowded presidential race since the country declared
independence in 1963, 15 people were registered as
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
Incumbent Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi, 73 and in power
for 19 years, is widely expected to win his last campaign with
another five year term.
</P>
<P>
His powerful rivals include Mwai Kibaki of Democratic Party of
Kenya, Wamalwa Kijana of FORD-Kenya, Raila Odinga of National
Development Pary of Kenya, Charity Ngilu of Social Democratic
Party and Martin Shikuku of FORD-Asili.
</P>
<P>
Ngilu and Wangari Maathai from Liberal Party of Kenya are the
first women ever to vie for the highest political office in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Oludhe's Economic Independence Party, established late
last month, is the youngest party in the race, and Moi's
37-year-old KANU (Kenya African National Union) is the oldest.
</P>
<P>
Other candidates are Munyua Waiyaki of United Patriotic Party
of Kenya, George Anyona of Kenya Social Congress, Kimani wa
Nyoike of FORD-People, Koigi Wamwere of Kenda, David Ng'ethe of
Umma Patriotic Party of Kenya, Godfrey M'Mwireria of Green
African Party, and Katama Mkangi of Kenya National Congress.
</P>
<P>
A presidential aspirant can be qualified as he (she) gets the
mandatory 1,000 signatures of supporters, but to be a legal Kenyan
president needs no less than 25 percent votes in at least five of
the country's eight provinces. He (she) must also get the highest
total.
</P>
<P>
If no candidate meets that condition, there will be a run-off
between the two top-placed candidates within 21 days of the
announcement of final results from the first ballot and the 25
percent rule will still apply.
</P>
<P>
For the parliamentary election, about 883 candidates from 23
parties are taking part in the race to the eighth parliament. The
candidate with the highest number of votes in each constituency
wins. KANU have already got 13 seats unopposed.
</P>
<P>
There are 8,466 candidates standing for elections in 2,955
local wards.
</P>
<P>
Voting will be carried out in as many as 12,754 polling
stations in 210 constituencies. All the polling stations are due
to open at 6:00 a.m. and close at 6:00 p.m. (0300-1500 GMT).
</P>
<P>
It is unable to predict when partial or final results will
be known. However, local observers say the results may come
in two or three days after the polling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
