<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sino-Japanese Cooperation Fruitful (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 28 (Xinhua) -- The overall development of
economic, scientific and technological cooperation between the
Chinese and Japanese governments focusing on using Japan's
Official Development Assistance (ODA) has been fruitful since
China's reform and opening-up drive was initiated two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
Economists here say that such cooperative projects have yielded
good economic and social results which have contributed to China's
development and played a positive role in promoting Sino-Japanese
friendship.
</P>
<P>
Since Japanese Prime Minister Masayoshi Ohira voiced his
support for helping China in its modernization drive during his
visit to China in 1979, China has become one of the key countries
receiving ODA. The Japanese government aims at strengthening
economic cooperation with foreign countries, through such
assistance in the form of loans, aid and technological cooperation.
</P>
<P>
China started using Japanese government loans through the
Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund of Japan in 1979 to purchase
equipment, materials and technologies for more than 100 projects
covering communications, energy and social infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
By 1997 the Japanese had committed to more than 2.084 trillion
yen in government loans, accounting for more than 40 percent of
such loans China has received from foreign governments.
</P>
<P>
These Japanese government loans have all been injected into
China's key projects to make up for insufficient capital in these
areas, thus promoting China's economic growth as well as the
common development of the two economies and bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, China also used Japanese export promotion program
loans of 70 billion yen for more than 280 projects in
export-oriented sectors such as light industry, textiles,
agriculture, animal husbandry, fishery and raw materials.
</P>
<P>
Along with the loans, China received 95 billion yen in Japanese
aid from 1981 to the beginning of 1997 for 80 projects in
education, medicine, agriculture, environmental protection and
social insurance.
</P>
<P>
Such aid resulted in a number of projects popular with Chinese
people such as the Sino-Japanese Friendship Hospital, the
Changchun Water Treatment Plant, the water improvement project in
Guizhou and the Minjiang flood control system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971228.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sino-Japanese Cooperation Fruitful (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Non-governmental scientific and technological exchanges between
China and Japan started in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
Since the normalization of Sino-Japanese diplomatic ties in
1972, bilateral governmental cooperation in scientific and
technological fields started to grow.
</P>
<P>
So far, the two countries have agreed to cooperate in five
aspects under bilateral agreements on scientific and technological
cooperation, environmental protection and nuclear cooperation,
technological cooperation through the Japanese International
Cooperation Agency and cooperation between different departments
of the two governments.
</P>
<P>
Under the bilateral scientific and technological cooperation
agreement, China and Japan have cooperated on more than 170
projects covering such fields as agriculture, metallurgy,
oceanography, meteorology, the environmental, disaster-prevention,
earthquakes, desert, biology and astronomy.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral technological cooperation has resulted in feasibility
studies for more than 70 large projects and investigation for
modernization of more than 70 medium-size enterprises across
China.
</P>
<P>
So far, Sino-Japanese scientific and technological cooperation
has grown from sending personnel to study in Japan and inviting
Japanese experts to China, to providing facilities and
documentation for China.
</P>
<P>
This year is the 25th anniversary of the normalization of
Sino-Japanese diplomatic relations. Leaders of the two governments
have exchanged visits, and have spoken highly of bilateral
economic relations.
</P>
<P>
The two governments and business communities in both countries
are working toward bilateral economic, scientific and
technological cooperation for the next century.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
