<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Government Urged to Focus on Education, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 28 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
been urged to focus its 1998 budget in the four areas of
education, health, agriculture and energy, the Guardian reported
today.
</P>
<P>
This is the result of a sample survey conducted by the
newspaper in Lagos State last week, when 705 usable responses
were derived out of 1,000 interviews.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that 73.3 percent of the randomly selected
adult citizens want the government to give topmost attention to
education in next year's budget.
</P>
<P>
For 51.8 percent of them, the government has been urged to
give lion's share of the 1998 budget to the provision of
qualitative health care and improved health care facilities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 37.7 of them would rather prefer the government to
prioritize agriculture in next year's budget so as to supply
abundant food supply for the people and export, thereby reducing
the country's overdependence on crude oil as the mainstay of the
economy.
</P>
<P>
About 22.8 of the respondents want the new budget to put more
funds in revamping the energy sector, while 20.6 percent called
on the government to devote the biggest chunk of the 1998 budget
to employment generation and creation of employment
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Other areas that caught the attention of the respondents
include improvement of the life of the rural populace (12.1
percent) and transportation (12.1 percent).
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted between December 18 and 22, also covers
such areas as road construction and rehabilitation, petroleum and
the value of the national currency, women's affairs,
telecommunications, defense, information, youth, prisons and
culture.
</P>
<P>
Another finding of the survey is that Nigerians are still
indifferent to the killer disease AIDS, as only 2.6 percent of
the respondents want more fund to be devoted to AIDS and other
sexually transmitted diseases in next year's budget.
</P>
<P>
Ironically, however, the survey reveals that as much as 58.3
percent of the respondents are skeptical of the government's
promise to release the 1998 budget by December 31, 1997, 30
percent of whom based their doubt on the antecedents of the
Abacha administration not to keep its promise.
</P>
<P>
While 32.5 percent believed the budget would be released
unfailingly by that date, 9.2 percent are indifferent as to
when the government might decide to release it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971228.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Makes Breakthrough in Generating Electricity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 28 (Xinhua) -- China expects to generate
1.135 trillion kilowatts-hour (kwh) of electricity and develop an
installed generating capacity of 250 million kilowatts (kw) this
year, ranking the country second in the world in both categories.
</P>
<P>
According to Shi Dazhen, Chinese minister of electric power and
general manager of the China State Power Corp., China has made a
historic breakthrough in electricity generation, investment modes,
operating mechanisms and management systems. A complete and modern
power industry has taken shape.
</P>
<P>
The minister made his remarks at the national power conference
held here today. He said that it is remarkable for the country's
power generation to maintain an annual average growth rate of 6.2
percent for five consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
And, for 10 years running, the large and medium-size generating
units with capacity ranging from 10 million kw to 15 million kw
have been put into operation annually.
</P>
<P>
China's power industry has recorded a growth rate of 8-to-9
percent since the establishment of the ministry of electric power
five years ago.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities
directly under the central government have met the target of
making electricity available to every village under their
jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
Ninety-five percent of the country's rural population should
have access to electricity by the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
Shi said that with Daya Bay and Qinshan nuclear power plants
now in operation, the country's sources of electricity have been
diversified. Hydropower generating units with capacity exceeding
four million kw annually have also been put into operation.
</P>
<P>
Large generating units each with a capacity of
200,000-to-300,000 kw have become the backbone of the country's
power grids, which account for more than 40 percent of China's
total installed power generating capacity.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the country has succeeded in setting up a
multi-channel fund collection system for power construction, with
funds from various localities and overseas topping 170 billion
yuan for constructing large- and medium-size generating units, and
accounting for 43.1 percent of the total investment.
</P>
<P>
The minister added that the all-around reform has started in
the country's power industry to transform the traditional
operating mechanism and management system, which has been
initiated by the establishment of the China State Power
Corporation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971228.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: Globalization Highlights Economic Malaise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, November 28 (Xinhua) -- Germany, a country that has
created its economic miracle in the post-war period like a fairy
tale and emerged as an economic power in Europe, has at last
found itself in a predicament in face of globalization of the
world economy.
</P>
<P>
For dozens of years, German-made goods have been taken as the
symbol of top-quality products, which has helped German
corporations like Siemens AG march into world markets away from
home.
</P>
<P>
Under the pressure of heated international competition now,
Siemens says it can no longer endure the high costs of doing
business at home.
</P>
<P>
It is sending more and more investment to and creating more and
more jobs in the United States, Asia and eastern Europe, where
taxes and labor costs run much lower.
</P>
<P>
No wonder competition in the wake of globalization today
involves much more than quality.
</P>
<P>
Factors like the swiftly developing information industry,
diversified customer demands, freer flows of capitals and
sophisticated technologies have made lower costs and prices,
investments overseas and localization of production equally
crucial for key corporations to occupy markets.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey showed 28 percent of Germany's 6,000 leading
companies are planning to move their production lines abroad over
the next three years. Nearly two-thirds of them attributed this to
high domestic labor costs as the main reason.
</P>
<P>
Such an exodus helps shed light on what is described by some
German economists as the worst structural crisis for the German
economy since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
As globalization is developing in depth around the world,
Germany's welfare-oriented social market economy, once working so
soundly to help achieve its economic miracle in the 1950s and
1960s, is becoming increasingly saddled with difficulties.
</P>
<P>
This year, the country saw its unemployment rate hovering at a
postwar record high of over 11 percent, economic growth lagging
behind the average of industrialized nations, its world market
share shrinking, and a huge deficit in investment flows and an
accumulated national debt of about 2,250 billion Deutsche marks
(about 1,268.3 billion U.S. dollars), twice that in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Germany also witnessed a dropping competitiveness, which ranked
the 25th in the world last year after 22nd in 1995 and fifth in
1993, said a report from the Geneva-based World Economic Forum.
</P>
<P>
All these occurred coinciding with globalization and some
Germans tend to put the blame on the latter. But it is more fair
to say that it is globalization and the resulting fiercer
international competition that have highlighted Germany's
fundamental structural problems.
</P>
<P>
A worker lives more comfortably in Germany than elsewhere in
the world. He earns about 30 U.S. dollars an hour on average --
nearly twice the level in the United States and Britain, has six
week holidays each year and a month's pay in extra as Christmas
bonus.
</P>
<P>
On the other side, German companies in 1993 contributed 250
billion marks (about 141 billion dollars) to non-wage labor costs
like employees' pension, health care, and unemployment insurances,
or 7.7 percent of Germany's total social security spendings.
</P>
<P>
The comparable percentage was 4.9 percent in the United States,
5.1 percent in Japan and 3.5 percent in Britain.
</P>
<P>
On top of this were high tax levies. Corporate tax bills of
western German enterprises added up to 64.9 percent of their
profits in 1995, compared with 45.3 percent in the United States,
59.2 percent in Japan and 33 percent in Britain.
</P>
<P>
German businesses also have to cope with overly protective
labor regulations, including high minimum wages and many
restrictions on dismissing employees. The laws are so strict that
employers are just reluctant to hire new workers in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
The companies in response moved production abroad. They have
invested 216 billion marks (about 121.8 billion dollars) abroad
since 1990, thus creating 500,000 new jobs overseas.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, about two million jobs were axed during the period
in Germany, which came partly as a result of the companies'
restructuring efforts to cut costs and sharpen their competitive
edge.
</P>
<P>
The German companies are still busy with merging, focusing
themselves on core businesses and adopting more flexible working
practices just as what most U.S. corporations did in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to ease burdens on enterprises and boost investment
and employment, the German government proposed this year reform
packages to overhaul the country's taxation, pension and
health-care systems. But all have been mired in setbacks.
</P>
<P>
The tax reform has been shelved due to the dispute between
government and the major opposition Social Democrats over how to
re-distribute the tax burdens and how to make up the financial
shortfall after tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
However, it is agreed by all that the reform is a must to
restore Germany's competitive position.
</P>
<P>
However, even with all these done, it could still be far from
enough.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts also pointed out that Germany has lagged behind
the Unites States and Japan in information industry, services and
technical innovation, as well as its still relatively smaller
business presence in the newly emerging markets in Asia and South
America.
</P>
<P>
They feared these factors, if not improved, would likely put
Germany in a disadvantageous position in future competition with
its major economic rivals.
</P>
<P>
But maybe a more tough job for the country is to foster an
entrepreneurial spirit of taking risks in its people, who have for
so many years got used to a cozy cradle-to-grave welfare system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
