<HEADLINE> Campus Cult Wars Kill 54 in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has recorded the death
of 54 undergraduates in institutions of higher learning
nationwide as a result of cult wars this year, the Sunday Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Several hundred students were maimed or wounded in the
violence unleashed on the campuses by the various campus cults in
their mindless rivalry and blood letting.
</P>
<P>
Although the mortality rate was of the same pattern with that
of 1996 when 46 students were killed in cold blood, the brigandry
and savagery that surrounded the campus blood letting this year
were of even more worrisome magnitude, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Quoting the Committee for the Protection of People's Dignity,
the newspaper said cult activists also gained momentum in the
secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
According to the committee, at least 70 suspected cult
militants were charged to court during the year, but only about
four cases have been decided so far.
</P>
<P>
As result, a worrisome dimension to the cult syndrome is the
increasing interest of children and wards of the elite in the
scourge, said the committee, which was established by former
President of the Students Union of the Lagos university Sowore
Omoyele.
</P>
<P>
Allegedly rusticated from the university ater mounting a
counter-attack on cult members in 1994, the former student leader
called on parents and university administrators to salvage the
situation fast.
</P>
<P>
Concerned about the increasing campus cult activities, related
authorities have taken some measures to fight against cultism.
</P>
<P>
Some students involving in cult wars have been expelled and
police squads have been stationed in some universities, including
the big-name University of Lagos, to avoid renewed clashes
between rival cult groups.  
</P>
</TEXT>
