<HEADLINE> Enduring Mindanao Peace in Sight: Philippine Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 28 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and
the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) have agreed to sign a
preliminary peace understanding by January 30 next year and a
final peace accord before June 30, Speaker Jose de Venecia said on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia, the ruling Lakas-NUCD party's presidential
candidate for next year's elections, made the announcement here
three weeks after he and MILF Military Commander Al Haj Murad
signed a joint press statement in the rebel stronghold in Camp
Abubakar, Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
But the statement was brought to Manila just now and released
here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In the joint statement, de Venecia and Murad said the
government and MILF peace panels would expedite the ongoing talks
so that an accord on peace in Mindanao could be signed before
President Fidel Ramos steps down on June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Under the Philippine Constitution, Ramos is not allowed to seek
re-election after his six-year term ends on June 30.
</P>
<P>
"We are one final step away from an agreement that would
guarantee an enduring peace in Mindanao," said Speaker de Venecia.
</P>
<P>
The speaker's visit to the MILF camp in November broke the
deadlock that threatened to derail indefinitely the peace process.
</P>
<P>
In the envisioned preliminary understanding, the MILF-held
areas of Buldon, Bareira and Matanog in Mindanao would be declared
as special development zones, according to a Philippine News
Agency report.
</P>
<P>
The 12,000-strong MILF became the major threat to peace in the
Southern Philippines after the government and the Moro National
Liberation Front, another rebel group, signed a peace accord last
year. The MILF rejected the peace agreement and continued its
fighting for an independent Muslim state.  
</P>
</TEXT>
