<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smokers in California to Lose Last Refuge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Smokers who have been
chased out of every other public places in California will soon
lose their last refuge - bars.
</P>
<P>
On January 1, smoking will be prohibited in bars throughout the
the state on the U.S. west coast.
</P>
<P>
Starting from 1995, the state banned smoking in all enclosed
workplaces, with the exception of bars, card rooms, hotel lobbies
and retail tobacco shops.
</P>
<P>
Now bar owners are required to post "no smoking" signs in their
establishments, to remove ashtrays and other cigarette-enticing
artifacts, and to tell nicotine addicts that they can't light a
cigarette especially after they have fired up.
</P>
<P>
Failure to do so could results in a fine of 100 dollars for the
first time, 200 dollars for the second and 500 dollars for
subsequent violations within one year. After the third offense, an
investigation could end up with a fine of up to 7,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
In San Francisco alone, the ban will affect approximately 1,000
bars, nightclubs and restaurants. Some tavern owners are afraid
that when the smoke clears, they won't have many customers
left.
</P>
<P>
But others acknowledged that more and more customers are
nonsmokers. Besides, the ban may also bring new customers who
don't get into taverns just for fear of secondhand smoking.
</P>
<P>
By sitting in a smoky bar for two hours, one sucks up as many
carcinogens as in smoking four cigarettes, according to the
American Cancer Society. It is estimated that between 4,200 and
7,000 Californians, and about 53,000 Americans, die each year from
the effects of secondhand smoking.
</P>
<P>
In another development, at least one state prison inmate has
claimed that he wants a reprieve from secondhand smoking.
</P>
<P>
In a lawsuit filed earlier this month, Gene Moran, serving a
three-year sentence for burglary, said that guards are not
enforcing state no-smoking rules and other inmates' cigarettes
have caused him health problems and emotional distress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971228.0079 </DOCNO>
