<HEADLINE> LTTE Rebels Rocked by Scandal of High-ranking Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 28 (Xinhua) -- The Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam (LTTE) has been rocked by a multi-million dollar financial
scandal which involved some of the organization's high-ranking
leaders, the Lankapuvath News Agency of Sri Lanka said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The news agency quoted its sources as saying that rebel leader
Velupillai Prabhakaran has discovered that some of his top aides
had swindled millions of dollars from the organization's fund.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that Lawrence Thilagar, former international
spokesman for the LTTE, and Nadarajah Muraleetharan, LTTE leader
in Switzerland, were summoned by Prabhakaran to his jungle hideout
in Sri Lanka's Northeastern district of Mullaitivu recently.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, they had siphoned LTTE funds into
their secret private bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
In one single case, Thilagar was alleged to have taken 100,000
dollars out of a 500,000-dollar LTTE fund, which came from a
company that sells pirated video and audio products.
</P>
<P>
Lankapuvath said the LTTE's international financial operations
were in such a disarray that even Prabhakaran's trusted arms
dealer Kumaran Pathmanabhan has been placed under surveillance.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting a 14-year-long ethnic war with
government troops in a bid to create a separate state of their own
in the north and east of the island nation.
</P>
<P>
The organization obtains its fund from voluntary donators and
its underground economic activities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
