<HEADLINE> Kuwait's Media Expect Cabinet Reshuffle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti newspapers have
been flooded with reports of an expected cabinet reshuffle or the
dissolving of the National Assembly during the holy month of
Ramadan due to start in a few days.
</P>
<P>
Newspapers, both Arabic and English, recently quoted
"highly-informed sources" as saying the country is on the verge of
"a big political settlement," which will lead to the resignation
of the Cabinet and exclusion of Finance Minister Nasser Al-Roudhan
in a new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Despite denial by some officials of such a situation, the
newspapers give an impression that the Gulf state, which has the
only parliament in the region, will see a highly charged situation
and hectic political activity before a settlement is reached.
</P>
<P>
Al-Roudhan, who passed an open parliament grilling in July over
alleged mismanagement, irregularities in handling public funds and
negligence, again fell a target of the religious groups and some
deputies who joined hands to attempt to grill the finance minister
for the second time.
</P>
<P>
Rumors have it that Al-Roudhan submitted his resignation before
the Gulf summit earlier this month, but he was asked to wait until
the meeting was over.
</P>
<P>
So far Al-Roudhan remained silent and did not refute the
resignation rumors.
</P>
<P>
The minister's alleged resignation and the strained relations
between the parliament and the government are manifestation of a
real political crisis that should no longer be ignored in the
country, many sources were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
So the current situation caused wide speculations about a
cabinet reshuffle and dissolving of parliament.
</P>
<P>
An article by Arab Times Editor-in-Chief Ahmed Al-Jarallah
quoted informed sources as saying that "discussions and
negotiations have been going on for the last few weeks to shape
out the reforms program," adding that "either the cabinet will
resign or the Assembly will be constitutionally dissolved."
</P>
<P>
Others, according to the newspapers, however, are of the view
that the situation does not require any "abnormal" solutions,
believing that the way out is through the resignation of the
Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti Crown Prince and Prime Minister Sheikh Saad
Al-Abdullah Al-Sabah was reportedly to have a plan of
appointing "strong and competent" members in the cabinet after
he returned home from a health recuperation in last September.
</P>
<P>
However, Kuwait's First Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign
Minister Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber Al-Sabah Saturday
categorically denied reports of a possible dissolution of the
parliament and said he "did not hear" about the resignation
of the finance minister.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the press for "fabricating tension" in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
