<HEADLINE> Iranian President Leaves for Turkmenistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami left here this morning for Turkmenistan, starting his
first foreign visit since he assumed office in August.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving Tehran, Khatami expressed hope that his first
foreign trip would be a source of blessing for the two nations of
Iran and Turkmenistan, saying that Iran considers itself
duty-bound to assist its neighbors, the newly independent
countries of the former Soviet Union in particular, in their
efforts toward progress.
</P>
<P>
"We must make use of the existing understanding to bring
progress, security and stability to the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Iran's official news agency IRNA, Khatami will
hold talks with high ranking Turkmen officials and attend the
inaugural ceremony of the gas pipeline between Turkmenistan and
Iran during his two-day visit to Turkmenistan.
</P>
<P>
The 200-kilometer pipeline was built between the two
neighboring countries at a cost of 195 million U.S. dollars. It
passes from Turkmenistan to northern Iran and will be connected
to another pipeline to reach Europe via Turkey.
</P>
<P>
As of next year, Turkmenistan will start its gas exports
through the pipeline with an initial annual capacity of 4
billion cubic meters. Iran will fetch a good revenue through
transiting Turkmen gas to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
During Khatami's visit, the Turkmen segment of the huge
fiber optics project connecting Asia to Europe will also be
inaugurated.
</P>
<P>
The project implemented by Iran's telecommunications company in
Turkmenistan is part of the Asia-Europe fiber optics project
from Shanghai, China to Frankfurt, Germany.
</P>
<P>
The 23,000-kilometer optical fiber goes through China,
Kyrgyzstan, Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan and Turkmenistan before
entering Iran. It will be connected to Germany after passing
through Iran, Turkey and Ukraine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
