<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Outgoing U.N. Special Envoy
on Afghanistan Nobert Holl expressed his hope here on Sunday that
different initiatives including those of the Group of Eight
Countries can be channeled for bringing about durable peace in the
conflict-torn country.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that different initiatives can be channeled in a
reasonable way and we can reach tangible results in foreseeable
future," Holl said in his farewell press conference, referring to
different efforts for realizing peace in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Holl, who relinquished his assignment as U.N. special envoy on
Afghanistan on Sunday, said that the Group of Eight Countries,
working under the U.N. and comprising six immediate neighbors of
Afghanistan and U.S. and Russia, should discuss the strategic
gains of Pakistan and Iran, the two vitally important countries,
in making peace in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The UN diplomat favored the role of foreign countries in making
peace in Afghanistan, declaring that past experience shows that
Afghans alone are "not capable of bringing about durable
settlement."
</P>
<P>
Holl called for materializing the idea of a broad-based
government in the strife-hit country as "it will be important in
the sense of nation building with representation from all ethnic
groups."
</P>
<P>
On former Afghan president Burhanuddin Rabbani's recent visit
to Pakistan, Holl said, "the visit was not a competition between
the U.N. and the individual countries."
</P>
<P>
"As a matter of fact Pakistan has been trying to bring about a
dialogue between Afghans and with the visit of Rabbani has
established its credentials as a neutral negotiator," he said.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that these efforts, which have received response from
Rabbani and the Taliban, will be coordinated under the UN
umbrella.  
</P>
