<HEADLINE> Zambia Resists External Pressure for Kaunda's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 28 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has
resisted external pressure for the immediate release of former
president and opposition leader Kenneth Kaunda, saying that the
courts will determine his guilt or innocence.
</P>
<P>
According to today's Sunday Times of Zambia, in an apparent
response to the calls for Kaunda's release from Washington and
South Africa, Home Affairs Minister Peter Machungwa stressed here
Saturday that Zambia is a sovereign state and will adhere to the
rule of law and human rights in determining the cases of those
implicated in the October 28 abortive coup.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the minister as saying that the Zambian
government is committed to the rule of law and will not break its
laws to suit an individual.
</P>
<P>
The government could not use the laws differently just because
someone is former president and has power and friends in high
places, said the minister, adding that "he should not be above
the law."
</P>
<P>
"We have a number of people who are detained and who we
believe were involved in the foiled October 28 coup and it would
not make much sense to release Kaunda leaving out the other
suspects," Machungwa noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that he was surprised that "America where the rule of
law obtains is saying we should not follow the law."
</P>
<P>
"Government will not follow the whims and fancies by people
who are friends of Kaunda. If those detained are innocent the
court will decide," the home affairs minister said.
</P>
<P>
Following the arrest and detention of Kaunda on the early
morning of Christmas Day, the U.S. and South Africa pressed the
Zambia government to release the 73 year-old veteran statesman,
said the government-owned newspaper.
</P>
<P>
A White House spokesman condemned the arrest and detention of
Kaunda and called for his quick release. He said in an undated
statement that "we call on the government of Zambia to release
him in the spirit of reconciliation and peace."
</P>
<P>
And South African President Nelson Mandela also called on the
Zambian government "to either bring Dr. Kaunda to trial
immediately or to release him from detention forthwith,"
according to a statement released Thursday by Mandela's office.
</P>
<P>
A number of African leaders besides Mandela have also
expressed their concerns over the arrest of Kaunda, who is
alleged to have connections with the failed October 28 coup
designed to topple the incumbent government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
