<HEADLINE> Khatami Reiterates Importance of Rule of Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami has reiterated that the exercise of authority should be
within the framework of the country's laws, according to Iran's
official news agency IRNA.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the seminar of provincial governors general
Saturday, Khatami said that in a law-oriented and law-abiding
society such a practice would not only instill dignity but also
protect and preserve the rights of the individuals in the nation.
</P>
<P>
No freedom is possible unless it is within the norms of
law and that any practice of freedom outside the limits and
framework of law either breeds a state of anarchy or foments
dictatorship in a society, he noted.
</P>
<P>
In recent days, many Iranian top officials including Supreme
Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, President Khatami, Interior
Minister Abdollah Nouri openly called for rule of law in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the Iranian leaders underlined the
importance of respect to laws because they felt that the Islamic
regime was threatened by unlawful actions inside the country,
particularly the factional violent conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said that violent fightings occurred recently
among political factions due to their differences and several
cinemas in Isfahan and Amol were stormed by radicals in a protest
to the screening of the controversial film the Snowmen which was
believed to be against the Islamic values.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian leaders warned that such illegal actions taken by
certain factions under the name of Hezbollah would damage the
regime's image both in the country and in the world.
</P>
<P>
Khatami urged the governors general to be alert to the
potential dangers from outside the country as well as within the
nation, saying that the duty of the government is to guarantee the
security of the nation and that the provincial governors are
empowered to act within their jurisdiction against any alien force
and their domestic lackeys who try to cause harm to Iran.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
