<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Economists Welcome New Taxation System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 28 (Xinhua) -- The introduction of
value-added tax (VAT) in Zimbabwe has been welcomed by economists
who say this will widen the tax incidence and shed off the burden
of taxation as the government will have a wide revenue base.
</P>
<P>
According to the Sunday Mail today, a survey by the local
paper last week indicates that the VAT system is quite popular
with industrialists and economists but there was a convergence of
views that there should be an effective tax paper education first
before the system is introduced.
</P>
<P>
Economist Howard Sithole said the VAT was a more efficient tax
than the present general sales tax as it would be more difficult
to evade.
</P>
<P>
The system was also self-enforcing, said Sithole, adding that
it required proof of documentation on the tax paid by suppliers.
Tax officers would therefore not engage much time in chasing
after defaulters.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the general sales tax, a single-stage tax paid by the
consumer right at the end of the trading chain, the VAT is a tax
levied on value added at each stage of production rather than
only on the final selling price, the report explained.
</P>
<P>
Chief economist of the Commercial Bank of Zimbabwe Danny Dube
said the present general sales tax had some loopholes as it
tended to exclude certain traders from the tax net.
</P>
<P>
"The present tax incidence is narrow. It needs to be widened
to ensure that more people pay tax and the tax burden on
individuals is lightened," he said.
</P>
<P>
The value-added principle is used in gross national product
accounting, to avoid double counting. Basically, the value added
tax is a sales tax of the multiple-stage type, but instead of
being levied on each turnover as the product progresses in stages
from the raw material form to purchase by the consumer of the
finished product, it is imposed on the increments of value-added
at each stage. 
</P>
