<DOCNO> XIE19971228.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Central, Western Parts Opening Wider </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, December 28 (Xinhua) -- The central and western parts of
China, a region which once lagged behind the coastal east in reforms
and opening up, are now making a new effort to narrow the gap.
</P>
<P>
The region accounts for more than 80 percent of the country's land
mass and 64 percent of its population, playing a decisive role in
China's economic prosperity as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Chances have come in recent years for the region to step up
reforms and open wider to the outside world, as the central
government began to shift its economic development priority
gradually to the central and western parts.
</P>
<P>
So, the state has opened another nine cities along the Yangtze
River, 13 border cities and all the capital cities in the region.
</P>
<P>
Investment environment and local infrastructure of the area
have been greatly improved by the development of the Yangtze River
watershed, construction of the Three Gorges project, operation of
the Beijing-Kowloon Railway, the second Eurasia Continental
Bridge, and the Nanning-Kunming Railway.
</P>
<P>
Ensuing funding from ministries and commissions for various
other major projects in the region is pushing forward the opening
up drive in the region.
</P>
<P>
To date, more than 150 countries and regions have opened
businesses in the area, involved in infrastructure and basic
industries such as energy, communications, and agriculture, as
well as finance, insurance, real estate and retails.
</P>
<P>
To bring more foreign investment into the region, departments
concerned plan to provide preferential policies for equipment
imports to those overseas-funded projects which meet certain
conditions, according to Zhao Guanghua, deputy head of the Office
of Special Economic Zones under the State Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
