<DOCNO> XIE19971228.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Minister Starts Visit to S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Liu Yegang, Zhao Yi)
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen arrived here this morning for a
five-day official visit to South Africa, during which a joint
communique will be signed to establish diplomatic relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Qian was greeted at the airport by Wang Xuexian, Director of
the Chinese Center for South African Studies, and officials from
the South African Foreign Affairs Department.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement issued at the airport, Qian said: "
Although far apart from each other, the Chinese and South African
peoples enjoy a long history of exchanges."
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese people forged a profound friendship of
comrades-in-arms with the South African people during their
protracted and arduous struggle for racial equality," he added.
</P>
<P>
Qian stated that the Chinese people heartily rejoice at the
birth of a new South Africa, and the peoples of the two countries
will continue to support each other in their efforts to build up
their nations and develop economies.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased to see that through the efforts of both sides,
the relations between our two countries are about to be
normalized," he noted.
</P>
<P>
This will open up new and broad vista for the development of
bilateral cooperation in various fields and the furtherance, on a
new basis, of the traditional friendship between the two peoples,
Qian said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese foreign minister will fly to Cape Town this
morning where he will meet South African President Nelson Mandela
and Parliament Speaker Frene Ginwala.
</P>
<P>
Qian, the highest-ranking Chinese official ever to visit South
Africa, will also have talks with his South African counterpart
Alfred Nzo and sign an official joint communique over the
normalization of relations between the two countries on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mandela announced in November last year that his government
would sever diplomatic ties with Taiwan and establish
comprehensive diplomatic relations with the People's Republic of
China before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Qian is scheduled to attend on January 1 the opening ceremony
of the Chinese Embassy in Pretoria, the administrative capital of
South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
