<HEADLINE> Moi Tipped to Win Tomorrow's Elections: Opinion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Results from a presidential election
opinion poll indicate that incumbent Kenyan President Daniel
arap Moi could win a landslide victory in December 29
general elections, Sunday Standard reported today.
</P>
<P>
The poll conducted by the Public Universities Research Team
(PURT) shows President Moi leading with 49.2 percent of the votes
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The poll results released last night predicted that Moi,
the presidential candidate of the ruling Kenya African National Union
(KANU) is poised to get more than 25 percent of votes in seven of
the country's eight provinces.
</P>
<P>
Under Kenya's law, the winning presidential candidate must
collect at least 25 percent of the votes in at least five of
Kenya's eight provinces.
</P>
<P>
PURT ranks Mwai Kibaki of Democratic Party second to Moi with
16.2 percent, Ford-Kenya's Wamalwa Kijana third with 12.7
percent, Raila Odinga of National Development Party (NDP) fourth
10.1 percent, and Charity Ngilu of Social Democratic Party fifth
9.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The poll predicted that the ruling KANU will gain a total of
119 parliamentary seats from the overall 210 while a combined
opposition will get 91 seats.
</P>
<P>
The poll results say that the ruling party will emerge more
nationalistic after tomorrow's elections with parliamentary seats
garnered in all eight provinces including Central Province where
it was locked out in the general elections in 1992.
</P>
<P>
PURT said that its results were arrived at after it conducted
opinion poll in all the 210 constituencies in the east African
country between December 12 and 23.
</P>
<P>
At least 200 respondents randomly sampled were interviewed at
each poll across the constituencies, the independent opinion poll
team noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
