<HEADLINE> Floods Kill 20 in W. Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 28 (Xinhua) -- A six-year-old boy was
killed when his house wall collapsed while he was asleep on the
Christmas day, bringing the death toll of floods in the Tabora
Region in west Tanzania to 20.
</P>
<P>
Tabora Regional Commissioner, Stephen Mashishanga, told the
Daily News that the boy, who was buried by the debris, was
identified as Mateo Ndomo, a resident of the Nduguru division.
</P>
<P>
Mashishanga said the rains have also displaced 13,000 people
in the region after their houses were destroyed by floods that
have swept the whole country since the start of this month.
</P>
<P>
Some of the victims were being sheltered in government offices
while others were staying with relatives or friends, the press
said today.
</P>
<P>
The regional commissioner said heavy rains are still pouring
down in the region and the damages may be bigger if they
persisted.
</P>
<P>
So far, no outbreak of water-borne diseases such as diarrhoea
and cholera had been reported and regional authorities were
taking preventive measures, Mashishanga said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in the Mara Region in the north, residents have
contributed 6 million Shillings (about 9,000 U.S. Dollars) and
materials to reconstruct bridges and roads damaged by the floods.
</P>
<P>
Mara Regional Commissioner Nemrod Lugoe, said Tamau village
has been flooded and 3,000 villagers had moved to primary schools
and Sunday markets to take shelter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
