<HEADLINE> Israel's Public Hospitals Resume General Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Israel's public hospitals
resumed the general strike today to protest against the planned
changes in the National Health Insurance system, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of doctors, nurses and administrative workers of the
public hospitals walked out at 8 O'clock this morning, and only
emergency services and vital departments are still functioning
normally.
</P>
<P>
The resumption of the strike came after the breakdown in
negotiations Saturday night between the Israel Medical Association
and the Treasury, which brought a halt to a one-day strike in all
the public hospitals Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The proposed changes in the health system, as part of the
Treasury-sponsored arrangements bill for the state budget of 1998
would allow each health fund to set its own basket of services,
thus increasing "competition", and demand that patients pay extra
charges of various treatments and medications.
</P>
<P>
The doctors are demanding that the proposals be removed
from the arrangements bill and be dealt with separately from
the state budget.
</P>
<P>
Yitzhak Peterburg, the director-general of the country's public
hospitals, said that the changes will bring about the
establishment of two separate health systems -- one for the
well-off and another for lower socioeconomic groups.
</P>
<P>
He noted that under the new law the average family will have
to pay over 1,000 shekels (about 280 U.S. dollars) extra annually
for visits to doctors, hospital emergency rooms, outpatient
clinics and other services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
