<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China City Increases Cooperation With Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, December 28 (Xinhua) -- This capital city of northeast
China's Heilongjiang Province is taking measures to promote trade
and economic relations with the Far East region of Russia, in a bid
to become a regional metropolis in northeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
The city plans to increase bilateral trade volume to two
billion US dollars by the year 2010, focusing on the Russian
cities of Yekaterinburg, Nakhodka, Vladivostok, and Chabarovsk, a
city government official said.
</P>
<P>
It has also begun to promote intergovernmental exchanges, and
agreed to set up a Sino-Russian Economic Coordinating Council, as
well as to improve the practice of tax collection and international
payments.
</P>
<P>
Harbin has established trade representative offices in the four
Russian cities. The offices have organized Chinese manufacturers
to hold exhibitions of high-quality Chinese goods.
</P>
<P>
The city opened Chinese name-brand products retail/wholesale
centers and bonded warehouses in Chabarovsky and Yekaterinburg,
respectively. The Xuanyuan Group opened a China commodity street
in Nakhodka, and the Sanxing Trade Company built a China furniture
center.
</P>
<P>
Harbin has quite a number of professionals specialized in
trade business with Russia, and convenient transportation by
water, air, train and highway. So it has every reason to expand
trade and economic cooperation with Russia, the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
