<DOCNO> XIE19971228.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: South Africa After Mandela (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Nelson Mandela, top
leader of South Africa's African National Congress (ANC), has
stepped down of his own accord as the ANC president at the just
concluded 50th ANC national conference in Mafikeng, North West
Province.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, while Thabo Mbeki was elected unanimously at the
five-day meeting by ANC delegates as the party's new chief,
Mandela, the South African president who led the movement to bury
apartheid and has been leading his people to build a new South
Africa, has given Mbeki, his deputy, a full stage by announcing
that he would not participate in the 1999 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffle of the ANC's leadership and the making of
comprehensive strategic decisions have drawn great attention not
only from people of all walks of life in South Africa but also
the world.
</P>
<P>
Will the latest ANC strategies and programs continue to work
without the 79-year-old Mandela? Mbeki, his successor, has given
the country and the world a convincing answer.
</P>
<P>
In his closing speech at the party's national conference,
Mbeki reaffirmed that the new leadership will stick to the
existing policy of national reconciliation, a course of action
taken by the ANC-led government ever since 1994 to maintain
social stability by tilting toward black people while taking into
account the interests of the whites.
</P>
<P>
It is generally acknowledged that after the abolition of
apartheid in 1994, the ruling ANC has been playing a key role in
national reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
In the past three and a half years, the party with a black
majority has spared no effort in restoring democracy and seeking
national reconciliation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to ANC's efforts, the central and local governments are
functioning normally with national unity maintained and the
national economy developing.
</P>
<P>
The ANC achievements owe a lot to its moderate policy based on
national reconciliation. Mandela, who is co-winner of the 1993
Nobel Peace Prize and enjoys high prestige at home and abroad,
has made tremendous contributions in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Three years after the abolition of the half-century-old
apartheid, South Africa has become a peaceful land where the
black and the white are living and working in harmony.
</P>
<P>
However, it is also true that today's South Africa is also
known for its high rates of crime and violence.
</P>
<P>
As the country's social transformation unfolds, the white
people living in clover began to feel uneasy as the democratic
reform is encroaching on their vested interest.
</P>
<P>
Pounded by the transformation, white extremists began
demanding to set up a so-called "white homeland" in hope to
retain their privilege as the white race.
</P>
<P>
Compared with the white, the disadvantaged black people, who
are eager to improve their living standards within a short period
of time, often complained about little change in their living and
working condition. Some of them have become so disappointed and
impatient that they even resort to armed robbery for quick
wealth.
</P>
<P>
The disappointment and resentment displayed by different races
have brought great pressure onto the ANC and the government.
However, it is unrealistic to weed out overnight the vestiges of
prolonged colonial rule and apartheid.
</P>
<P>
To solve the problems, Mbeki noted that instead of giving up
its national reconciliation policy in face of the Opposition, the
ANC will continue with the social transformation. Only when the
black and the white people are treated equally can social
stability be achieved, Mbeki stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the ANC would establish a mechanism which
will give all races and parties easy access to constructive
suggestions and criticism, thus paving the way to better
understanding and cooperation between the government and the
Opposition.
</P>
<P>
A new social system always encounters new problems and
conflicts. In the past three years, a large number of black
people who were short of professional training had been employed
by government organizations. Corruption, low efficiency and
bureaucracy, along with worsening social security, have posed
grave threats to the new born democracy.
</P>
<P>
The ANC-led government is giving priority to the fight against
increasing corruption and crimes, said Mbeki, adding that it was
not fair to attribute all the problems left by the apartheid
period to the current administration.
</P>
<P>
To settle these issues, the ANC head noted, it takes not only
time but also support and cooperation from all people in the
African country.
</P>
<P>
Only when more jobs are created, national economy developed
and the life of the black people remarkably improved, can the
social problems be solved fundamentally, said the upcoming leader
of the country. He pledged that the government is doing its best
to achieve this goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
