<DOCNO> XIE19971228.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southeast Asian Currency Crisis May Hit Sri Lanka: IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 28 (Xinhua) -- The Southeast Asian currency
crisis which has caused economic havoc in a number of countries is
bound to have an impact on the economic growth in Sri Lanka, an
official of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) said here
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Resident Representative of IMF in Colombo Anton Op de Beke said
that companies from Southeast Asian countries may scale down their
investments in Sri Lanka due to their financial problems. Tourism
from those countries to Sri Lanka could also be affected.
</P>
<P>
But he added it's too early to say how big the impact would be.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said the Sri Lankan Rupee is being depreciated
constantly, thus helping the Sri Lanka Central Bank offset the
differences in inflation rates between Sri Lanka and its trading
partners and keep the currency competitive.
</P>
<P>
Since the crisis began to hit Southeast Asia in July,
currencies in Thailand, the Philippines, Singapore, Indonesia and
Malaysia have depreciated between 10 to 35 percent, leading to
large-scale bank closures and layoff of employees.
</P>
<P>
The economic pains also caused political instability in some
countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971228.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: South Africa After Mandela (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The South African economy grew at about three percent in both
1995 and 1996. It is estimated that the growth rate this year is
about two percent, far below the six percent blueprinted in the
government's growth, employment and redistribution (GEAR)
macro-economic strategy adopted last year.
</P>
<P>
At present, the economy faces many difficulties, among which
are fluctuating exchange rates, bad behavior of major sectors
like manufacturing and mining, overflowing money supply and slow
input of domestic and foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Bleak as the economic picture is, it is already a big
achievement to maintain positive growth since the country is
undergoing profound political, economic and social
transformation.
</P>
<P>
At the party's national conference, resolutions were adopted
to cut down budget and reduce public spending, streamline
government structure and continue to implement the Reconstruction
and Development Program initiated in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The conference also resolved that the private sector and
small- and medium-sized enterprises be engaged in promoting
investment, development and the settlement of labor-management
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, with its rich natural resources, sound
infrastructure and advanced management, is already the number one
economy in Africa.
</P>
<P>
In the following years, the economy is expected to continue
its growth so that the country could maintain its position as
leader of the entire continent in trade and investment
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
To win the 1999 general election, the ANC adopted a strategy
of enhancing party unity, seeking cooperation from other
black-based political parties and maintaining high profile.
</P>
<P>
Before the conference, Mandela struck a conciliatory note with
the largest black opposition, the Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP),
calling for a merger of the two parties.
</P>
<P>
The two parties were long-time rivals due to policy
differences, especially the one over the proposed autonomy of
Kwazulu-Natal Province where the IFP is based. The defusing of
tensions between them has led to significant reduction in
politically motivated violence in the Natal region.
</P>
<P>
Whether the initiative is finally realized or not, the shift
from conflict to cooperation between the two parties will be
certainly conducive to political stability in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mandela voluntarily quit the post of party president at
Mafikeng conference and declined nomination for the party's
National Executive Committee, its top decision-making body
between national conferences.
</P>
<P>
According to him, he would act as an ordinary member of the
ANC and would retire from active politics in 1999.
</P>
<P>
As Mbeki is already the de facto head of state, Mandela said,
he is fully confident that the ANC without him would win the 1999
election and Mbeki will become the new state president and lead
South Africa into the 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971228.0116 </DOCNO>
