<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Population Growth Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Population growth in Bangladesh
has edged downward from 2.5 percent to around 2.2 percent while
contraceptive prevalence rate (CPR) has risen from 8 percent to 45
percent during the past 18 years, according to recently-released
World Bank report.
</P>
<P>
The report said fertility has also declined from around 7
percent to 3.3 percent during the 1975-93 period.
</P>
<P>
Fertility has declined rapidly as people continue to express
their willingness to have smaller families and to delay first
child birth, the report added.
</P>
<P>
There has been a rapid increased in CPR, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Infant mortality has declined to 77 in 1000 live births in 1994
as against 111.5 in 1981 while life expectancy has increased to 58
years in 1994 against 54 years in 1981, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
Over the last 20 years, Bangladesh built up an extensive health
care infrastructure, and has 3,775 family welfare centers or
health sub-centers and 349 sub-district health complexes, the
report stated.
</P>
<P>
Family planning services are now widely available as both
government and non-government organizations are playing an
important role, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971228.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Le May Doan Betters 500 Meters Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Catriona Le May Doan bettered
her 500-meter world record on Saturday at the Canadian Olympic
speed skating trials in Calgary.
</P>
<P>
Le May Doan was timed in 37.71 seconds, nearly 0.2 seconds off
the 37.90 record she set at a World Cup meet on the same ice on
November 22.
</P>
<P>
Olympic silver medalist Susan Auch was second in 38.46 seconds
with Linda Johnson Blair third in 39.23.
</P>
<P>
The skaters will be ranked after a second race later on
Saturday. The top three qualifies for the Winter Olympics in
Nagano, Japan, next year.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 500 meters, Jeremy Wotherspoon stood first in the
two-race series after a 35.84-second sprint. Kevin Overland was
second and Michael Ireland third.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 5,000, Mark Knoll clocked 6:44.84 to grab the sole
Canadian spot available in the event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
