<HEADLINE> Uruguayan Army Chief Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Uruguayan Army
Commander-in-Chief Lt. Gen. Raul Mermot submitted his resignation
Friday night and requested to go into retirement.
</P>
<P>
According to sources close to the government, Mermot's action
was in protest against a decree of rehabilitation granted by the
government to 41 officers who had been done wrong during the
military dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting held Friday night, President Julio Maria
Sanguinetti and Defense Minister Raul Iturria had tried to
persuade him to stay. However, Mermot insisted on his resignation,
the sources said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the political parties in the country supported the
decree, while the military expressed discontent with it.
</P>
<P>
Gen. Fernan Amado is expected to succeed Mermot as new army
Commander-in-Chief next February. For the time being, Gen. Nestor
Bertrin will be in charge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
