<HEADLINE> S'pore PM to Join 8000 Nationals at Condolence Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong will join 8,000 Singaporeans at a national condolence
service on Tuesday for the 104 people who died in the SilkAir
plane crash on December 19, the Sunday Times, the Sunday edition
of the Straits Times, said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the national condolence service will be a
45-minute service in which religious leaders from the
Inter-Religious Organization representing nine faiths will say
prayers. Prime Minister Goh is also expected to address the
service.
</P>
<P>
SilkAir flight MI185 crashed into the Musi River near
Palembang, Indonesia, on December 19, with 97 passengers and seven
crew members on board. No one survived in the tragedy. This was
the first air mishap ever happened in the civil aviation history
of Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Former president of Singapore Wee Kim Wee, who chairs a
committee that is organizing the event, will make a short speech
at the service, which will be held at the Singapore Indoor Stadium
at 6 p.m. on Tuesday. Prime Minister Goh will address the service
too, the Sunday Times report said.
</P>
<P>
It also said that SilkAir will make arrangements to fly in
relatives of the foreign passengers on board flight MI185 for the
service here. Of the 104 air crash victims, 58 were from
Indonesia, Malaysia, the United States, France, Britain, Germany,
Japan, Bosnia, Austria, Australia, India, New Zealand, and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
