<HEADLINE> Kyrgyzstan President Outlines New Year Tasks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Kyrgyzstan President Askar
Akayevich Akayev said Friday that the strategic goal next year
will be to raise the people's living standards, Itar-Tass
reported.
</P>
<P>
Another task is to strengthen the integration process between
member countries in the Central Asian Association and the Customs
Association.
</P>
<P>
Akayev said Kyrgyzstan's gross domestic product rose by 6
percent and its agricultural output 8 percent in 1997. The
inflation rate was within 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Based on this year's economic improvement, Kyrgyzstan will,
with the help of international organizations, "try to accomplish
the strategic goal of raising the people's living levels next
year," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said his country will strengthen cooperation with Kazakhstan
and Uzbekistan, in the fields of energy, food and water
conservancy. A free trade zone will be set up among the three
countries.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Kyrgyzstan will take active measures to boost the
export of industrial products, he said. 
