<HEADLINE> Thailand Considering More Spending Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai said Saturday it was his biggest concern that the
government might not be able to collect enough revenue to meet
expenditure in fiscal 1998, according to the Bangkok Post Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Chuan admitted that having a balanced budget of 800 billion
baht (17.8 billion US dollars) was virtually impossible, let alone
having a surplus of one percent of gross domestic product (GDP),
as required by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) for issuing
more fund to Thailand from the IMF-arranged 17.2 billion dollar
bailout package.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that the government may have to ask the
IMF to ease its bailout package conditions, particularly the
requirement of the one percent of GDP surplus in the budget.
</P>
<P>
Three rounds of slashes had been made to the 1998 budget to
reduce it to 800 billion baht from over 1,000 billion baht.
</P>
<P>
Chuan said, "I would like to tell the people straight that
despite best efforts to increase revenue and to cut spending, if
there is still a revenue shortfall, it might be necessary to have
a tax increase. But the people will be told in advance and we will
try to cause minimum impact to the poor."
</P>
<P>
He said there would not be another budget cut, but
belt-tightening steps would be taken to bring spending down,
adding that the government would do its best to promote exports
and tourism to bring in much-needed foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Sanan Kachornprasart said on Saturday that
position allowances for senior officials in state enterprises
under the ministry are to be cut, following a 20 percent salary
cut for cabinet and parliament members for a one-year period.
</P>
<P>
The military has also announced plans to scrap its weaponry
purchases in fiscal 1998, which ends in September.  
</P>
</TEXT>
