<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientific Farming Popular In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Agricultural techniques have
contributed some 40 percent to China's grain production increases
over the past few years, and an increasing number of farmers now
turn to scientific farming for higher returns.
</P>
<P>
Nong'an County in northeast China's Jilin Province is cited as
a typical example. It has been the country's leading
grain-producing county in the past three years, with an annual
production of two million tons, or one-240th of the national
total. China has more than 2,000 counties and county-level
cities. It harvested over 480 million tons of grain last year.
</P>
<P>
The Nong'an County Association for Science and Technology often
provides technical services for farmers. Li Yuhua, chairman of the
association, has been known as the "king of insects",or expert on
controlling insects.
</P>
<P>
A science and technology development center was set up
accordingly to offer solutions to any questions raised by farmers.
</P>
<P>
The county has expanded an agricultural technique spreading
network to every rural household, with part-time or full-time
senior researchers and professors working for it. And more than
1,000 farmers have been promoted to the status of agricultural
technicians.
</P>
<P>
Farmers also set up science and technology associations of
their own. Now, there are 112 such associations with nearly
15,000 members.
</P>
<P>
And officials at all levels are held accountable for expanding
the use of useful farming techniques. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
