<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, December 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN -- A German population foundation Saturday predicted that
at least a fourth of the world population are expected to suffer
from fresh water shortage by the year 2050.
</P>
<P>
According to the Hannover-based German Foundation of World
Population, more than 430 million people, or about eight percent
of the world population, are currently living in countries which
are plagued by water shortage.
</P>
<P>
By mid next century, the figures are expected to rise to about
two billion or even 6.8 billion with the world population expected
to grow to between 7.7 billion and 11.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi Oil Minister Amir Mohammed Rashid Saturday
asserted his country's readiness to export crude oil to world
markets soon after the ratification of the new food distribution
plan from the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The oil reservoirs in the seaports of Iraq's Bakr and Turkey's
Ceyhan are ready for the export and contain large quantities of
oil, Rashid told reporters after talks with Jordanian Minister of
Energy and Mineral Resources Mohamed Saleh Hourani here.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq will give priority to the oil firms of friendly
countries in signing deals under the third stage of the
oil-for-food deal with the U.N..
</P>
<P>
