<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dangerous Cargoes Traverse Panama Canal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CANAL, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Some 229 ships loaded
with dangerous cargoes went through the Panama Canal this year, a
report from Panamanian environmentalist groups revealed Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The document shows that most of the cargoes that were carried
through the interoceanic waterway in 1997 were gasoline, kerosene,
radioactive materials, pesticides, alcohol derivatives and
chemicals.
</P>
<P>
Ships from Europe or Asia are more likely to be loaded with
dangerous materials. In August this year, a Japanese ship called
Pacific Pintail plied the canal carring a cargo of nuclear
materials.
</P>
<P>
This enraged the environmentalist groups, among them
Greenpeace, which warned that if a person got near a container
opened by accident, "he or she would die in just a few minutes."
</P>
<P>
However, Canal Commission officials said that the
transportation of such kinds of cargoes are in accordance with the
treaties established by the International Maritime Organization,
and the U.S. Coast Guard Service.
</P>
<P>
As it is stipulated in the treaties concerning the permanent
neutrality and operation of the canal, the Panama Canal must be
open to the transit of all the ships, as long as they pay the toll
fee and do not commit hostile actions against the waterway.
</P>
<P>
The Panama Canal is 80 kilometers (50 miles) long and can allow
more than 13,000 ships of diverse types to transit between the
Pacific and the Atlantic Oceans each year. enditem
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
