<HEADLINE> Nowen Wins Women's Slalom at Lienz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Sweden's Ylva Nowen won a World
Cup women's slalom competition at Lienz, Austria, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Nowen registered a combined a winning time of one minute 35.42
seconds from two runs, 0.28 seconds ahead of Italy's slalom world
champion Deborah Compagnoni.
</P>
<P>
Urska Hrovat of Slovenia timed 1:36.19 to grab the third spot.
</P>
<P>
Nowen's victory was only her second in eight seasons following
her triumph at Val d'Isere last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Nowen, who led after the first run, overcame a descending fog
and a worn piste to remain on the top.
</P>
<P>
The Swede now extended her lead in the slalom standings to 280
points.
</P>
<P>
Zali Steggall, the first Australian woman to win a World Cup
race in Park City, Utah, is second on 185 points after finishing
sixth on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Katja Seizinger, who normally excels in the faster
disciplines, finished seventh and extended her already commanding
lead in the overall World Cup standings to 866 points.
</P>
<P>
Her compatriot Hilde Gerg, who was 13th fastest, is overall
second on 674 points while Compagnoni is third on 503. 
</P>
</TEXT>
