<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Railway Line to be Built in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 28 (Xinhua) -- The Litang-Qinzhou Railway is
scheduled to open in December of 1998 for the 40th anniversary of
the founding of the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, according to
local sources.
</P>
<P>
The railway, a key project included in the country's Ninth
Five-Year Plan, will start from the intersection of the
Beijing-Guangzhou Railway, China's north-south artery, and
Xiangtan-Guizhou Railway running through the mid-south region, and
stretch to Qinzhou, a seaport city on Beibu Bay.
</P>
<P>
The construction will involve excavating 387 tunnels and
building 315 bridges.
</P>
<P>
With the completion of the railway, three southern sea outlets
in the autonomous region will play more prominent roles in marine
transportation for cargo from the two north-south railways. The
railway can save more than 200 kilometers compared with loading
cargo in Zhanjiang in south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The three ports include Qinzhou, Fangcheng and Beihai, with the
latter two connected to the railway by Nanning-Kunming Railway, a
trunk line recently completed in the southwest region.
</P>
<P>
The railway will run through poverty-stricken mountainous areas in
the eastern part of the region where no railway traffic has gone
before. Local officials have placed high hopes on the railway to
help the region rise out of poverty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971228.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Fourth of World Population to Suffer from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 27 (Xinhua) -- A German population foundation
today predicted that at least a fourth of the world population are
expected to suffer from fresh water shortage by the year 2050.
</P>
<P>
According to the Hannover-based German Foundation of World
Population, more than 430 million people, or about eight percent
of the world population, are currently living in countries which
are plagued by water shortage.
</P>
<P>
By mid next century, the figures are expected to rise to about
two billion or even 6.8 billion with the world population expected
to grow to between 7.7 billion and 11.2 billion, the German
foundation quoted a recent study conducted by the international
organization Population Action International (PAI) as saying.
</P>
<P>
The PAI study also cautioned that the increasing rivalry over
the scarce water resources in some regions, with the
Euphrates-Tigris Basin, the Nile Basin and the southern Africa in
particular, could lead to open conflicts among the countries
concerned.
</P>
<P>
While the Middle East and North Africa are hardest hit by water
shortage today, the sub-Saharian Africa would be the most
problematic region in the next 50 years with its population
expected to double its current level during the period, the study
predicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
