<DOCNO> XIE19971228.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Outlines Medicare Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today outlined the nation's Medicare reforms that make cancer
screenings less expensive for 39 million older Americans by New
Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
Under the balanced budget agreement that Clinton negotiated
with Congress, the nation's 39 million Medicare beneficiaries
will be guaranteed regular tests for breast, cervical and
colon-rectal cancer.
</P>
<P>
Studies show that early detection of these cancers can boost
survival rates as high as 90 to 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Nearly every American family has been touched by the shadow of
cancer," Clinton said in his weekly radio address. "By detecting
cancer early on we offer our loved ones one of the greatest gifts
of all _ the gifts of life, health and many holidays to come."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the new program will offer annual breast X-rays
for all Medicare-eligible women age 40 and older.
</P>
<P>
The program will cover pay for pap smears and pelvic exams
every three years, or annually for women who are at high risk for
cervical cancer.
</P>
<P>
Diagnosed early, the cancer can be treated with a 90-percent
survival rate, but the rate drops to 7 percent when the cancer is
missed until its advanced stage, said Clinton. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
